    <paperBody>
        <page n="01" image="pa.fr.vs.1861.07.06.01">
            <div type="a">
                <column>2</column>
                <head>Seizure of the Steamer St. Nicholas--Capture of three Merchant Vessels</head>
                <origin>Baltimore Exchange</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Recounts the seizure of the St. Nicholas by Confederates disguised as
                    passengers.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>3</column>
                <head>The Killed and Wounded</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>List of the wounded from the Williamsport and Hagerstown skirmishes.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>5</column>
                <head>Important Arrival</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Announces the arrival of Prince Polignac of France in Richmond as a guest
                    of President Davis.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <pageNote>Various items of national news and Southern news. Bottom of page
            illegible.</pageNote>
        </page>
        <page n="02" image="pa.fr.vs.1861.07.06.02">
            <div type="a">
                <column>2</column>
                <head>Where Will it End?</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt>"The bad management and in some instances, down-right villainy apparent in
                    our army affairs is beginning to receive very general condemnation in the right
                    corner."</excerpt>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Criticizes the mishandling of army affairs and alleges downright corruption
                    that even certain Republican papers cannot countenance.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>2</column>
                <head>Malice</head>
                <origin>American Volunteer</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Criticizes Col. John W. Forney for cozying up to the Republican
                    establishment by criticizing James Buchanan, his former benefactor, in his bid
                    to be re-elected Clerk of the House.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>2</column>
                <head>Personal</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The Valley Spirit asks that subscribers pay what they owe.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>3</column>
                <head>The Views of Mr. Douglas</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt>"If any one ventures to express a hope that there will be no more
                    bloodshed, these 'Democratic' abolitionists are the first to pronounce him a
                    traitor."</excerpt>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Accuses "former" Democrats such as John Forney of opposing any measure to
                    adjust national difficulties. As they are professed admirers of the late Sen.
                    Douglas, the item quotes a pro-settlement speech from Douglas at length.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>4</column>
                <head>The World and the Tribune</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Reports that the rivalry between the Republican New York World and the
                    opposition New York Tribune has become quite intense.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>4</column>
                <head>The Hundred Dollar Bounty</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Announces a one hundred dollar bonus to anyone who serves for three years.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>5</column>
                <head>Hostile Attitude of France</head>
                <origin>Correspondence of the Philadelphia Inquirer</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Reports suspicion of French overtures toward the South.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>6</column>
                <head>Frederick A. Guion</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Reports the arrest of Guion in New York for circulating a position
                    requesting that Lincoln effect a settlement with the South without bloodshed.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <pageNote/>
        </page>
        <page n="03" image="pa.fr.vs.1861.07.06.03">
            <div type="a">
                <column>1</column>
                <head>Swear Him</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Alleges that Solomon Chase, the Secretary of the Treasury, should be
                    required to take the Oath of Allegiance as he advocated dissolution at an 1848
                    Abolition Convention.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <pageNote/>
        </page>
